Note:
NETWORK PORT - 16-bit Transport-Layer Port Number (Tier 1)

Implements the NetworkPort value type representing a 16-bit TCP/UDP port
number per RFC 793 (TCP) and RFC 768 (UDP). Classification follows the
IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry:
  - Well-known ports        0..1023     RFC 6335 section 6
  - Registered ports        1024..49151 RFC 6335 section 6
  - Dynamic/private ports   49152..65535 RFC 6335 section 6

The privileged-port concept (port < 1024) derives from BSD socket
conventions and is enforced on Linux via the CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE
capability. On Windows the equivalent privilege requires Administrator
or NT AUTHORITY\NETWORK SERVICE membership.

Representation:
  A NetworkPort is stored as a Runa Integer 0..65535 inclusive. The type
  is nominal in API documentation but encoded as an integer to remain
  zero-overhead at the call site.
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let PORT_MIN be 0
Let PORT_MAX be 65535
Let PORT_WELL_KNOWN_MAX be 1023
Let PORT_REGISTERED_MIN be 1024
Let PORT_REGISTERED_MAX be 49151
Let PORT_DYNAMIC_MIN be 49152
Let PORT_PRIVILEGED_MAX be 1023

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Construct a port from a raw 16-bit value with explicit validation. Returns
-1 on out-of-range input so callers distinguish the error sentinel from
the legitimate value 0 (the "any port" wildcard at bind time).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range check 0..65535. Identity assignment.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Out-of-range inputs are rejected because they would otherwise be
truncated by the kernel when passed to bind/connect, leading to
unexpected port collisions.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "port_from_u16" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is less than PORT_MIN:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is greater than PORT_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning
Return the raw 16-bit integer behind a NetworkPort. Provided as an
explicit accessor so call sites convey intent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Identity with bounds validation.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No external input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "port_value" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is less than PORT_MIN:
        Return -1
    End If
    If port is greater than PORT_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return port
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Well-known port range 0..1023 per RFC 6335 section 6. These ports are
assigned by IANA to specific protocols (SSH=22, HTTP=80, HTTPS=443, etc.)
and binding to them typically requires elevated OS privileges.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
0 <= port <= 1023.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Tools that scan or open well-known ports should warn users since the
ports are reserved for documented services.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "port_is_well_known" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is less than PORT_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If port is greater than PORT_WELL_KNOWN_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Registered port range 1024..49151 per RFC 6335 section 6. Assigned by
IANA to specific applications but bindable without OS privileges.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1024 <= port <= 49151.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Application code can bind freely without root or Administrator rights.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "port_is_registered" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is less than PORT_REGISTERED_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If port is greater than PORT_REGISTERED_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Dynamic/private port range 49152..65535 per RFC 6335 section 6. Used by
the operating system as ephemeral ports for outgoing connections; also
the recommended range for short-lived application-internal ports.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
49152 <= port <= 65535.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Servers should avoid this range for stable services because OS-allocated
ephemeral ports may collide.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "port_is_dynamic" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is less than PORT_DYNAMIC_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If port is greater than PORT_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Privileged port range 0..1023. Binding requires CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE on
Linux, or equivalent privilege on other systems. This predicate is an
alias of port_is_well_known but the name documents the OS-privilege
implication explicitly at the call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
0 <= port <= 1023.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Process launchers must drop the capability after bind to follow the
principle of least privilege.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "port_is_privileged" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is less than PORT_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If port is greater than PORT_PRIVILEGED_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
